http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/Hundreds-worship-Thiruvabharanam/article14015856.ece

Hundreds of Ayyappa devotees, majority of them women, thronged the Kakkatt Koickal Sree Dharma Sastha Temple at Perinad, near Vadasserikkara, to worship the sacred jewellery, Thiruvabharanam, which was brought in a customary procession from Sabarimala to be taken to the Pandalam palace on Friday.Adorned with jewelleryThe Kakkatu Koickal is the only temple other than the Lord Ayyappa Temple at Sabarimala and the Valiyakoickal Sastha Temple at Pandalam where the presiding deity is adorned with the Thiruvabharanam every year.It has been a custom and practice to decorate the Ayyappa idol at the Kakkatt Koickal Temple with the sacred jewellery when the procession carrying the sacred jewellery reaches there on the return journey to Pandalam after the Makaravilakku festival at Sabarimala every year.It is believed that the king of the erstwhile Pandalam kingdom had stayed at the Perinad temple to monitor the construction work at the Ayyappa Temple at Sabarimala centuries ago.The procession carrying the Thiruvabharana was accorded a rousing reception on its arrival at Perinad in the afternoon.The presiding deity at the Perinad temple was decorated with the Thiruvabharanam by 2 p.m., and the Melsanthi performed Aarati, later.Women devoteesHundreds of women devotees from the neighbouring States of Tamil Nadu, Andhra Pradesh, and Karnataka too have reached Perinad to worship the Thiruvabharanam, as entry for women in the age group of 10 to 50 years is not allowed at Sabarimala.Towards AranmulaThe temple will remain open till 2 a.m. on Saturday for the devotees to have darshan.The Thiruvabharanam procession will then proceed to Aranmula in the morning.The sacred jewellery will be taken back to Pandalam from Aranmula on Sunday morning.